Women Empowerment: The Bechdel Test

(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bechdel_test) The Bechdel test (/bkdl/ BEK-dl), also known as the BechdelWallace test, is a measure of the representation of women in fiction. It asks whether a work features at least two women who talk to each other about something other than a man. The requirement that the two women must be named is sometimes added.

Do movies that pass the Bechdel Test get rated more highly?

We want to see whether movies that pass the Bechdel Test are rated more highly than movies that fail the Bechdel test. We examine this for men and for women separately.

Among Women:

Chi-Square Test

From a chi-square test on the proportion of movies getting a 4+ rating, the p-value is significant, and indicates that the movies that fail the Bechdel Test have a higher proportion of 4+ ratings.

## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   passed_bechdel n_ratings_4_plus n_total
##   <chr>                     <int>   <int>
## 1 Failed                     5817    9919
## 2 Passed                     5541   10155
## [1] "Proportion of females that rate >=4 for movies that passed Bechdel: 0.545642540620384"
## [1] "Proportion of females that rate >=4 for movies that failed Bechdel: 0.586450247000706"
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions with continuity correction
## 
## data:  female_ratings$n_ratings_4_plus out of female_ratings$n_total
## X-squared = 33.847, df = 1, p-value = 5.961e-09
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.02700737 0.05460804
## sample estimates:
##    prop 1    prop 2 
## 0.5864502 0.5456425

Among Men:

Chi-Square Test

From a chi-square test on the proportion of movies getting a 4+ rating, the p-value is significant, and indicates that the movies that fail the Bechdel Test have a higher proportion of 4+ ratings.

## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   passed_bechdel n_ratings_4_plus n_total
##   <chr>                     <int>   <int>
## 1 Failed                    17153   29504
## 2 Passed                    17767   31771
## [1] "Proportion of males that rate >=4 for movies that passed Bechdel: 0.559220672940732"
## [1] "Proportion of males that rate >=4 for movies that failed Bechdel: 0.581378796095445"
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions with continuity correction
## 
## data:  male_ratings$n_ratings_4_plus out of male_ratings$n_total
## X-squared = 30.552, df = 1, p-value = 3.25e-08
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.01428377 0.03003247
## sample estimates:
##    prop 1    prop 2 
## 0.5813788 0.5592207
